svg.title: plumb

g.desc:
There are to be faucets at high and middle altitudes for each of the green houses.
The roof area (1500sf) collects rain which is delivered by a gutter to the rain cistern
g.title: Green Houses and roof

g.desc: Input from top cistern internal pump pumps to washer cistern
g.title: Washer

g.desc: Supplied with flushing water first with water stored in a washer cistern (filled whenever there is a wash) and secondly by the top cistern.
g.title: toilet

g.desc: One is permanently plumbed with city water The other is switched, later, to the non-potable rain water system.
g.title: sinks

g.desc: Initially uses city water but a switch of pipes allows non-potable usage
g.title: Shower

g.desc:
Heat supplied to house by pumping water from Hot-Warm cisterns.
Whole house heated by one efficient radiator with a fan, perhaps located just south of the garage entrance
Cold water (from the rain cistern) can also be circulated here
In theory these can be located also wherever there is the H/W lines, Eg at the two 'pumps and connectors benches'
g.title: Household Heat

rect.desc: 3x4 ribing at 3foot interval from 5ft above floor to roof
rect.title: *rib

g.desc:
The top cistern has input pumped up to it from the rain cistern Its output is everywhere water is used Eg warm cisterns, shower, sinks, green houses...
About 50g
Its output can be pressurized but the pump must failsafe so water still flows when electricity killed
g.title: top cistern

g.desc: The pond or rain garden or ...? catchs overflow of the rain cistern
g.title: Pond

g.desc:
The rain cistern is the storage system for all the water driving the rest of the system Input is from 1500sf of roof area filtered by a bioSand filter
Output is pumped up to the top cistern periodically
Also cycled through cooling tower as needed to keep a constant cold temperature
This cold water can be fed through the 'heating' radiator for air conditioning
5000g or more in capacity
g.title: rain cistern

g.desc: The ground reference is formed by several thousand feet of PEX tubing (for durability) buried, distributed, under the foundation It can also be used for cooling by pumping its water through the heating pipes
g.title: Ground reference

g.desc: A 'ground-reference' is made by flowing water through several thousand feet of PEX tubing placed under the slab Water flowing through it is kept at ground temperature with exposed ends near the HVAC pumps This reference cools potential Stirling engine, peltier cells, etc for power
g.title: *ground reference cistern piping

g.desc: A 'ground-reference' is made by flowing water through several thousand feet of PEX tubing placed under the slab Water flowing through it is kept at ground temperature with exposed ends near the HVAC pumps This reference cools potential Stirling engine, peltier cells, etc for power
g.title: *ground reference cistern piping

g.desc:
The biology part of the BioSand filter is encouraged to grow very tall into an 8 foot tall greenhouse watered from above by roof runoff and recirculated water from the rain cistern.
This keeps the water in this cistern cool it also encourages deep roots for better filtration
sides of greenhouse can be simply 2x8 sheets of clear corrugated roofing The "greenery" (fill) could be Hops growing up a string air would draft by convection from a chimney effect
g.title: Cooling Tower

g.desc: This cistern is buried and receives the outflow from all drains It is periodically pumped up to the BioSand input to the Rain cistern for reentry to the usage system Only Black water is not thus recycled
g.title: Gray water cistern

g.desc: The pumped outflow of the washer is stored in here for use by the toilet When it is inadequate the slack is from the general rain system
g.title: Washer cistern

g.desc: The Warm cistern(s) receive cooled water from heating the house thence to hot, warmed by suns heat
g.title: Warm water cistern(s)

g.desc: The Hot cistern(s) receive heated water via solar heat converter from warm containers Heated output to house (power etc) thence to warm for recycling
g.title: hot water cistern(s)
Hot Cisterns
g.desc: The Hot cistern(s) receive heated water via glycol/water heat converter from warm containers Heated output to house (power etc) thence to warm til recycled
Exchange heat from 10% glycol mix in evacuated tubes to water in cistern storage
g.title: Heat Exchanger

g.desc:
Final output to the city sewer system from toilet, sinks, showers etc
Potential overflow of overflow (of rain cistern to pond) likely only for code compliance
g.title: City Sewer

rect.title: pump and connectors benches
rect.desc:
pumps and connectors to all sources and destinations are collected together here so that they can be controlled by future developments eg computer control.
This connector bench is in both the cistern and the shop containers.
Specifically pairs from rain cistern/cooling tower hot water cistern Top cistern (may just be in cistern container)

g.desc: Sun heated 10% Glycol/h2o mixture heat converted to water storage (from warm to hot containers) One or two initially expandable to four
g.title: solar hot water panels

g.desc: Clicking goes to an article on Abengoa The first US Solar powered system Initially there are not plans for power However allowances(benches) are made for future use of the stored solar heat, eg with Peltier Cells, Stirling engines or steam turbines as they did in Abengoa
g.title: Abengoa power plant
